* LuaLoad::    Loading Lua sources.
* LuaMatch::   Lua conditionals.
* LuaModify::  Changing requests and responses in Lua.
* Stash::      Sharing data between Lua invocations.
* LuaBackend:: Lua backends.
* Lua API::
@end menu

@node LuaLoad
@section Global Lua Configuration
  Lua sources are loaded from the global @code{Lua} section, using two
statements: @code{Load} and @code{LoadGlobal}.  These take as argument
the name of a Lua source file to parse and load.  As usual, relative
pathnames are looked up in the @ref{include directory}.

The @code{Load} statement loads the file to per-thread Lua
interpreters, while @code{LoadGlobal} loads it to the global one.
Example usage:

@example
@group
Lua
    Load "auth-bearer.lua"
End
@end group
@end example

If the file ends with a @code{return} statement, it is loaded as in
Lua @code{require}.  The return value is then available in Lua global
variable whose name is obtained from the filename using the following
procedure:

@enumerate 1
@item
Remove the @samp{.lua} suffix.

@item
Unless first character is a letter of latin alphabet or underscore,
add underscore at the beginning.

@item
In the resulting string, replace each character other than letter,
digit or underscore with an underscore.
@end enumerate

Thus, if the file @file{auth-bearer.lua} ends with a @code{return},
the returned value will be available in Lua as @code{auth_bearer}.

You can also supply variable name explicitly, as second argument,
e.g.:

@example
@group
Lua
    Load "auth-bearer.lua" "bearer"
End
@end group
@end example

Of course, you can use as many @code{Load} (or @code{LoadGlobal})
statements as there are files you wish to load.

This section can also be used to modify Lua search paths.  Two
statements are provided for this purpose: @code{Path} modifies search
path for Lua source files (@code{package.path}), and @code{CPath}
modifies search path for dynamic libraries (@code{package.cpath}).
Both statements add their argument at the beginning of the
corresponding @code{package} path.  For example:

@example
@group
Lua
    Path "/usr/share/pound/?.lua"
    Load "auth-bearer.lua" "bearer"
End
@end group
@end example

Notice that @code{Path} statement has no effect on where @code{Load}
looks for its argument (it always uses @command{pound} include path
to locate relative file names).  Instead, it affects @code{require}
statements in loaded Lua sources.

@node LuaMatch
@section Lua conditionals

  Lua functions are most commonly used to implement new conditions,
that can be used to select the @code{Service} section to use.  Such
conditions are applied using @code{LuaMatch} statements in
@code{Service} sections.  The @code{LuaMatch} statement takes at least
one argument: the name of Lua function to call.  It can be followed by
any number of string values, which will be passed to the function as
its arguments.  Before being passed to the function, these values
undergo backreference expansion and request accessor interpretation
(@pxref{Request modifications}).

  The first argument can be either an unqualified name, as
@samp{mycond}, or a fully qualified one, as @samp{modname.mycond}.
Use the latter form to call functions defined in modules.

  Information about HTTP request is provided to Lua functions via
the built-in variable @code{http.req}, described in @ref{Lua API}.

  To illustrate the concept, here's the definition of a Lua test that
returns @code{true} if the value of a header named in its first argument
matches any of its remaining arguments, treated as anchored Lua patterns:

@example
@group
function isheader(name, ...)
   local args = @{ ... @}
   for _, pat in ipairs(args) do
      if string.find(http.req.headers[name], "^"..pat.."$") then
         return true
      end
   end
   return false
end
@end group
@end example

Supposing that this function is defined in file @file{isheader.lua},
it can be used as follows:

@example
Lua
    Load "isheader.lua"
End
ListenHTTP
    ...
    Service
        LuaMatch "host" "foo[.]bar" "www[.]fo+[.]bar"
        Backend
            ...
        End
    End
End
@end example

 As a more practical example, the function below implements
@dfn{Bearer} authorization scheme.

@example
local bearer = @{@}
local jwt = require 'jwt'

function bearer.ok(secret)
   -- Read in the Authorization header.
   local bh = http.req.headers['Authorization']
   if bh == nil then
      return false
   end

   -- Check if it starts with "Bearer".
   local n, k = bh:find('%s+')
   if n == nil or bh:sub(1,n-1):lower() ~= 'bearer' then
      return false
   end

   -- Extract the token and parse it.
   local j, err = jwt.parse(bh:sub(k+1))
   if err ~= nil then
      return false
   end

   -- Verify the token.
   if not j:verify(secret) then
      return false
   end

   -- Check expiration time.
   if j.payload.exp ~= nil then
      local exp = tonumber(j.payload.exp)
      if exp == nil then
         return false
      elseif os.time() < j.payload.exp then
         return false
      end
   end

   return true
end

return bearer
@end example

@noindent
@xref{jwt.lua}, for the implementation of the @code{jwt} module.

 The following configuration fragment uses @code{bearer.ok} function
as a condition, to reject requests without a valid bearer token:

@example
@group
Service
    Not LuaMatch "bearer.ok" "secret"
    Rewrite response
        SetHeader "WWW-Authenticate: Bearer realm=\"Restricted access\""
    End
    Error 401
End
@end group
@end example

@node LuaModify
@section Changing requests and responses in Lua
@cindex LuaModify
  The @code{LuaModify} configuration statement instructs
@command{pound} to invoke a Lua function, ignoring its return value.
In other words, the function is called for its side effects,
whatever they are.

  Syntactically, the statement is similar to @code{LuaMatch},
discussed in the previous section: the function name is supplied as
its first parameter and the arguments, if any, as its remaining
parameters.  Only string arguments are allowed.

  @code{LuaModify} can appear anyplace where other request modification
statements are allowed: i.e. in @code{ListenHTTP} (or
@code{ListenHTTPS}), @code{Service}, @code{Match} and @code{Rewrite}
sections.

  Most often this statement is used to modify the incoming
request before sending it out to the backend, or the response before
returning it back to the client.  To do so, the function invoked by
@code{LuaMatch} can use the @code{http} Lua module, discussed in
@ref{lua-http}, in particular its fields @code{http.req} and
@code{http.resp}.

