@node Cookie injection
@subsection Cookie Injection
@cindex cookie injection
  Cookie injection is a special technique which ensures that
requests from a client are always forwarded to the same backend, even
if the backend server in question does not provide any mechanism for
session tracking.  It works as follows.  Upon first connection,
@command{pound} adds to the backend response a @code{Set-Cookie}
header with a unique cookie generated for this purpose.  This ensures
that further requests from that client will bear this cookie.  Then,
it will suffice to configure @command{pound} to use that cookie for
session tracking (@pxref{Sessions}), and all subsequent requests from
that client will go to the same backend.

  In this subsection we will show how to implement cookie injection
in Lua using @code{LuaModify}.

  Let's start from the Lua code.  We need a function that,
being invoked with the name of cookie as its argument, will check if
that cookie is present in the request and if not, will create it by
adding a @code{Set-Cookie} header to the response from backend:

@example
function inject(name, ttl)
@end example

Here, @var{name} supplies the name of the cookie to check for, and
@var{ttl} provides its time-to-live in seconds, which is used if the
cookie needs to be set.

Functions for operating on cookies are supplied by the @file{cookie.lua}
module, described in @ref{cookie.lua}.  To generate unique session
identifiers, we will use the
@uref{https://luarocks.org/modules/luau-project/lua-uuid, lua-uuid}
module.

  The resulting Lua module can then be written as follows:

@example
local _M = @{@}

local uuid = require('lua-uuid')
local cookie = require('cookie')

-- Unless cookie @var{name} is already set, create and initialize it
-- to a unique session identifier.  @var{ttl} supplies @code{Max-Age}.
function _M.inject(name, ttl)
   local cookie = cookie.get(name)
   if cookie == nil then
      cookie.set(name, tostring(uuid.new()), ttl)
   end
end

return _M
@end example

  Suppose this program is saved in file @file{mksess.lua}, located in
@command{pound} include path.  First, this program needs to be loaded
to @command{pound}.  This is done in the global @code{Lua} section:

@example
@group
Lua
    Load "mksess.lua"
End
@end group
@end example

  Then, the @code{Service} section which should implement cookie
injection, must be configured to track sessions by the value of a
cookie, and the @code{inject} function must be called on each backend
response.  Suppose the cookie used for session tracking is named
@samp{poundsession}.  Then:

@example
Service
    Session
        Type Cookie
        TTL  300
        ID   "poundsession"
    End
    Rewrite response
        LuaModify "mksess.inject" "poundsession" "300"
    End
    ...
End
@end example

@noindent
Notice, that @var{ttl} argument to @code{mksess.inject} matches that
in the @code{Session} section.

@node Stash
@section Sharing data between Lua invocations
@cindex stash
  Sometimes it is necessary to share data between Lua functions used as
conditions and modifiers in @command{pound} configuration file.  An
obvious way of doing so is using Lua global variables.  This approach,
however, poses one major problem: values stored in globals will
persist not only when processing a single HTTP request, but also
between different HTTP requests, and this can cause undesirable
side effects.

  To avoid this, @command{pound} provides a special built-in variable
@code{stash}.  Its value is a table whose contents persist only while
a singe HTTP request is being processed.  Applications can
fill it with whatever values they like.

  To illustrate its use let's change the @code{bearer} module from
@ref{LuaMatch}, so it can be used to select the service to use based
on JWT claims.  First, the @code{bearer.ok} function should store the
parsed JWT object in stash before returning.  Its last lines will then
look like:

@example
@group
   stash.bearer = j
   return true
end
@end group
@end example

  Then, we implement a new method, which checks if the hostname given
as its argument is listed in one of the JWT claims:

@example
@group
function bearer.urlOK(host)
   return stash.bearer ~= nil and
          stash.bearer.payload['http://' .. host] == true
end
@end group
@end example

  Now this method can be used as a conditional to select the service
to use as shown in the example below:

@example
@group
Service "auth"
    Not LuaMatch "bearer.ok" "secret"
    Rewrite response
        SetHeader "WWW-Authenticate: Bearer realm=\"Restricted access\""
    End
    Error 401
End

Service "foo"
    LuaMatch "bearer.urlOK" "foo.com"
    Backend
        Address 127.0.0.1
        Port 8081
    End
End

Service "bar"
    LuaMatch "bearer.urlOK" "bar.com"
    ...
End
@end group
@end example

The service @samp{auth}, same as in the previous example, verifies
that the request carries a valid bearer token and, if so, saves off
the JWT for further use.  Subsequent services make use of this saved
value to verify if the corresponding claim is true: the service
@samp{foo} is selected if the claim @samp{http://foo.com} is true, and so on.

@node LuaBackend
@section Lua backends
  Lua extensions can also be used to define new backends.  Similarly
to conditions, a function implementing a backend can have an arbitrary
number of arguments.  It is not supposed to return any values, though.
Instead, before returning, it should define the response to be returned to the
client.  It does so by initializing fields of the internal variable
@code{http.resp}:

@table @code
@item code
This field must be assigned the HTTP status code (an integer
value in the range 100 to 599).  If it is not initialized after the
backend function returns, @command{pound} will respond with the
default @samp{internal server error} page.

@item reason
This is a textual reason corresponding to the status code.  This value
is optional.  If not initialized, @command{pound} will use the default value
for the returned status code, if it is one of the codes supported
internally (@pxref{Error definitions}).  Otherwise the reason field
will remain empty.

@item headers
A table of response HTTP headers.

@item body
Response body as a string.
@end table

  Here is an example of Lua backend function.  The function below
can be used to return meaningful error status if the JWT authorization
implemented in previous sections fails.  It supposes that function
@code{bearer.ok}, before returning on error, initializes @code{stash}
fields @samp{error} and @samp{error_description} to the error code and
textual description, correspondingly.

@example
@group
function bearer.error_backend()
   local text = 'Bearer realm="Restricted access"'
   if stash.bearer.error ~= nil then
      text = text .. ', error="' .. stash.bearer.error .. '"'
      if stash.bearer.error_description ~= nil then
         text = text .. ', error_description="' .. stash.bearer.error_description .. '"'
      end
   end

   http.resp.headers['WWW-Authenticate'] = text

   http.resp.code = 401
end
@end group
@end example

To use this backend, we modify the @samp{auth} service as follows:

@example
@group
Service "auth"
    Not LuaMatch "bearer.ok" "secret"
    LuaBackend "bearer.error_backend"
End
@end group
@end example

